huntBios.GENERAL_INFORMATION: The public lands are primarily US Forest Service lands managed by the Uinta-Wasatch-Cache National Forest and Wildlife Management Areas managed by the UDWR. There is a large amount of private property on the unit as well, including many CWMU’s.
huntBios.SAFETY_CONS:
ATTENTION-The US Forest is planning on a few prescribe burns this fall that might interfere with some hunters hunt. Please be aware. Salt Lake City, Utah, September 13, 2019 – Uinta-Wasatch-Cache National Forest fire personnel plan to conduct a prescribed burn in the Sheep Creek area September 18, 2019 – November 30, 2019 when weather conditions allow. The project area is located in Utah County, approximately 30 miles east southeast of Spanish Fork, Utah, and northwest of Soldier Summit from Highway 6. The burn unit includes approximately 5,927 acres. This prescribed burn is part of a vegetation project that included mechanical treatment in 2013 through 2017.HWY 150 Here is a link to the USFS facebook page for more information. https://www.facebook.com/US-Forest-Service-Uinta-Wasatch-Cache-National-Forest-147726224920736/ Make sure someone knows where you plan to camp and when you will return.

Camps should be kept clean to prevent bear incidents. Food should be kept inside vehicles or bear-proof containers
huntBios.WEATHER_CONS: The weather on this hunt unit can vary dramatically during the hunting season.  Be prepared for rain, lightening, snow, wind and heat.  Early fall snow storms occur regularly in this area during this hunt.  Most years the snow will melt off within a day or two.  Be prepared for dry or muddy conditions.

huntBios.BIOLOGIST_NOTES:
General Considerations: This unit is a General Season hunt unit and is not managed to be a trophy unit but every year a few really nice bucks are taken. There are many CWMUs on this unit and a list of these can be found on the UDWR webpage.

Migration Patterns: Deer on this unit migrate down in elevation for the winter and typically from East to West, with most of the deer wintering on Wallsburg WMA, Sheep Creek and Diamond Fork canyons.

Mule Deer rut: The mule deer rut usually runs from mid Nov.-mid Dec. so it does not affect this hunt.

Recommended areas to hunt: There are numerous areas to hunt on this unit.

The areas surrounding Strawberry Reservoir, Sheep Creek, Diamond Fork, Hobble Creek, American Fork canyons, Mt. Timpanogos are excellent for deer hunting. They are easy to access with many roads and trails and camping areas. This of course leads to many people hunting these areas. There are very few areas on this unit without a road in the general area. This unit has very large aspen stands, oak brush can hold a lot of deer in the early fall. In the summer there are deer in the more open higher areas, but once they get pressured by hunters they will move into the lower, thicker tree stands. These areas are difficult to hunt, because of the leaves on the trees and fewer open areas to glass with optics. There are also many lower areas with several different browse species, including; oak brush, service berry, mountain mahogany, bitter brush, snow berry, sage brush, etc. These areas also have deer in them during the hunt, but at a lower density. All ways look for areas that deer are watering in.

Some areas to hunt include the following:
Strawberry Reservoir area- Try Indian canyon, Clyde Creek, Mud Creek, Squaw Creek, Horse Creek, Main canyon and Strawberry ridge.
Sheep Creek area- Try any of the waters ( First to Sixth) along Ray’s Valley road.
Diamond Fork- Diamond Fork is a mixture of public and private.
Hobble Creek- Right Hand fork is mostly public land, Left Hand Fork is mostly private land.
American Fork Canyon/Mt. Timpanogos-This area is steep and rugged.
Timp WMA-This area is real brushy but can be good hunting.
Wallsburg WMA-This WMA is mostly open sagebrush. Hunting can be good in October.

huntBoundaryInfos.CAMPGRND_INFO: All Campgrounds on this unit are managed by the US National Forest Service. Camping outside of official campgrounds is also permitted on most of the Forest. Please direct all questions regarding campground availability and other camping questions to the US Forest Service. Maps and camping regulations are available on their websites. Uinta-Wasatch-Cache National Forest website: http://www.fs.usda.gov/uwcnf
huntBoundaryInfos.COUNTY_ROAD_INFO:
PROJECT DESCRIPTION Central Federal Lands Highway Division (CFLHD), in partnership with Wasatch County, Utah County, and the United States Forest Service (USFS) is planning to improve Strawberry Sheep Creek Road, a 31.9 mile route between US-6 and US-40. This road is really 
ROAD CLOSURE CONSIDERATIONS The key objective is to construct these roadway improvements while minimizing impacts to public users. To facilitate public safety, certain segments of the road will be closed during various construction activities. When the road is open, delays up to 30 minutes can be expected. The construction schedule is subject to change. During road closures, no motorized vehicles will be permitted on the route. Adjacent Off Highway Vehicle (OHV) trail routes will continue to be open during road closures. Where a potential conflict between an OHV and construction equipment is possible, the OHV access will be restricted for public safety. Emergency access will be permitted at all times.
ROAD CLOSURE PRELIMINARY SCHEDULE
a combination of three smaller routes, Sheep Creek – Rays Valley Road (FR 70051); Unicorn Ridge – Indian Creek Road (FR 70042); and West Side Strawberry Road (FR 70131). The construction work will be split into four segments: Segment 1 (FR 70051) begins at the MP 0.0 (intersection with US-6) and ends at MP 7.0 (FR 70042). The work on Segment 1 consists of pavement rehabilitation including patching, crack sealing, and chip sealing. Segment 2 and Segment 3 (FR 70042) begins at MP 7.0 and ends at FR 70131. The work on Segment 2 and 3 consists of roadway bench widening, paving, drainage improvements, and safety improvements. Segment 4 (FR 70131) begins at the intersection with FR 70042 and ends 3.75 miles north of the intersection. The work on Segment 4 consists of pavement rehabilitation, pulverizing, and paving with subexcavation as needed.

huntBoundaryInfos.ATV_VEH_ACCESS: All roads and ATV trails on this unit are managed by the US Forest Service and are covered on their Travel Management Plans. Please direct all questions regarding which roads and trails ATVs can be operated on to the US Forest Service. Maps can also be purchased online at: http://www.fs.usda.gov/uwcnf
huntBoundaryInfos.PRIV_TRIBE_LAND_ISSUES: There are many CWMU’s on this unit. General Season Deer Permits are not valid on CWMU’s. All other private land requires written permission before hunting.
huntBoundaryInfos.BOUNDARY_DESCRIPTION: Salt Lake, Summit, Utah and Wasatch counties—Boundary begins at I-80 and I-15 in Salt Lake City; east on I-80 to US-40; south on US-40 to the Strawberry Bay Marina road; south on this road to USFS Road 042 (Indian Creek road); south and west on this road to USFS Road 051; south on this road to US-6; west on US-6 to US-89; northwest on US-6 to I-15; north on I-15 to I-80 in Salt Lake City. Excludes all CWMUs. USGS 1:100,000 Maps: Nephi, Provo, Salt Lake City. Boundary questions? Call the Springville office, 801-491-5678.
